</div>It's anecdotal, but in my circle of friends, who all like PC gaming over consoles, I'm the only one that cares enough to hunt for mods, install packages, beta test them and all that other BS. Most look for the original releases and play them exclusively.  <br />
<br />
There are PLENTY of gamers who use PCs but don't maximize their potential. You could argue PC gaming is where it is today because a) consoles are still limited use platforms and b) they haven't developed a controller good enough to replace a key board and mouse, not because modding and LAN play makes the business go 'round. It's the quality of a game that sells it, not just the potential for users to make it better. <br />
<br />
The future is moving toward gaming networks where players have a much smaller stake in the games they play. And I think you'd be surprised how a large percentage of gamers, who are all younger than you or I, are ok with that. <br />
<br />
And I've never, ever met a more conservative, intractable group of gamers than the ones who STILL play CS and the like. Ever. The fact they're religiously playing games over 10 years old speaks as much to the benefit of modded content as people's ability to play the same damn game until their hands fall off. <br />
