    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/openq.gif" width="30" height="30" ></td>
    <td>
		<div align="left" style="font-size: 12px; color: #999999; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;">Some moron who doesn't care about not having shitty ping's opinion is irrelevant when it comes to gaming, let alone the amount of stuff you cannot do without dedicated servers (league play, PUGs, clan servers, hell, clans in general).</div>
		</td>
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/closeq.gif" width="30" height="30" align="right"></td>
  </tr>
</table>
</div>In the case of GFWL and DoW 2, the network wasn't that hot at release and yeah, people were pissed. It took some time to iron out but it's relatively stable now. I didn't get into MP.  <br />
<br />
This is exactly like the reaction over at the D2 forums when Blizz announced no private server support for the game, and the DoW 2 with GFWL. The freakout rests on the assumption that the infrastructure will be terribad, which isn't a guarantee on either side. In MS's case, the assumption turned out to be right. <br />
<br />
Considering how much money is going into MW2 (and D2/SC2), and that there's no alternative way to play MP now, Blizzard/Activision know their network's credibility rests on its performance. <br />
<br />
And because clans can't host their own servers, there can't be clans....? Pfft. League play I'll give you, even though it's likely IW will handle competitive play on its end. It's been done other places already, and Blizzard is talking about it for SC2 and D2. <br />
<br />
So all the outrage strikes me as premature. Same thing happened with DoW 2. The integration of Steam/WindowsLive had everyone freaking out that there'd be no modded content. A few months after release, they put out a map tool and there was custom content. I haven't kept up with how the LAN works, but last I knew you couldn't do it.</div>
