    <!-- message -->
    <div align="left" id="post_message_489397"><div align="center" style="margin:5px; margin-top:5px; ">
<table width="85%" border="0" align="center" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0" bgcolor="#333333" class="bbcodeQUOTE">
  
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/openq.gif" width="30" height="30" ></td>
    <td>
		<div align="left" style="font-size: 12px; color: #999999; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;">What do you mean by smaller stake?</div>
		</td>
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/closeq.gif" width="30" height="30" align="right"></td>
  </tr>
</table>
</div>Where gamers don't own the servers, they don't own the content (maps, skins, mods, what have you) and in some cases, where they don't even own physical copies of the games anymore. Networks like Steam are effectively licensing us the right to game on their network. It's still in a state of flux, and it will never go 100% in either direction...but what has been true for consoles is rapidly becoming true for PCs as well...that developers are granting less control to players and retaining it for themselves. <br />
<br />
Compared to the days where every gamer had a 12 foot high stack of physical copies, a dedicated server machine for the flavor of the month and when most MP was handled not by the dev house but the players...times are a changin'.</div>
