    <td>
		<div align="left" style="font-size: 12px; color: #999999; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;">To Toprem:<br />
<br />
Really?  There's nothing like Diablo?  Dungeon Siege 1 and 2, Titan Quest and Expansion, Sacred 1 and 2 (2 is on consoles, even)...  that's just from the stack of games I have on my desk.  Hell, Champions of Norrath and Return to Arms is pretty Diablo like.  Unless you mean the &quot;atmosphere&quot; of devils and demons and stuff - and even then, those other games have parts like that if nothing else.<br />
<br />
I could download maps on the servers I played on - but that was typically random.  I was the guy RUNNING the server for my friends when we played.  So yeah, I had to do a lot of clicking and stuff.  I was pretty heavy into modding/mapping for UT2003/4 when I played it all the time - I didn't do mods, but I helped folks run websites and did betas and gave feedback and etc.  My ideas made it into a few of them, even if I wasn't officially involved.  So no, for me, it wasn't as simple as &quot;connect and download a map.&quot;  It never has been.  I'll download huge amounts of maps and play them, then toss the crap ones.  Some of the best fun I ever had was a map I found on some random obscure fan site that I would NEVER have had otherwise.  It was a remake of a Quake 3 map with teleporters in space, and we would have like, 4 of us versus a billion bots, heh.<br />
<br />
Matchmaking will likely be able to be overridden - it's unlikely you can ONLY play with your matches (some people are ranked low, and wanna jump right in, etc).  And if it has 8 or more players able to play at once in a MP match (which it would be silly not to) - some dude's house connection can't host that.  Do you really think that Halo 3 with 32 people is hosted off Bob's connection next door?  There's servers, dude.  Sure, if you wanna do standard co-op, with 2 people - it won't be on a server.  Otherwise, there will be servers hosting it.<br />
<br />
PS:  PC Gaming isn't leading anymore.  It hasn't for a while.  PC Gaming is for the folks with way more money than brains (for equipment, not the games - as a lot of games get pirated).  I play games on my PC still, but my Xbox gets way more love.  My PC is using a 2 year old video card (8800gt) - I wanna get a new one, but... I'd rather buy Arkham Asylum and MW2 for my Xbox.  Also, replace my xbox with a new elite.  Also, get a ps3.  Oh, and what PC game is going to make me twitch for it?  Borderlands on my Xbox is making me twitch that I haven't gotten up and run to the store yet (which is because I do NOT have the cash for it, heh).  Will it be out for PC?  Yes.  Should I just download and pirate it for PC?  Maybe.  I'm 28 now, I don't want to think about it, or dig for it, or go find mods and addons.  I wanna click a button on my controller, drop $5, and be done.<br />
<br />
To Nenjin:<br />
<br />
Clans aren't going anywhere.  They'll find a way.  Especially on the PC side.<br />
<br />
Second, again, PC gaming isn't going away because with the current consoles, it's easy to create a PC port (and vice versa)...  especially for Xbox 360.  Microsoft made it that way on purpose.  The PS3 is a different story, which is why PS3 exclusives don't end up on PC - Xbox 360 stuff almost always does.  Truthfully?  Even the control scheme isn't always better on PC.  I played Prototype on my PC, and desperately wanted a controller.  Playing Sacred 2 on my Xbox...  well, I kinda want a keyboard (only for more buttons).  Playing Gears of War?  I'd never even consider a keyboard and mouse, the controller works perfectly.  Call of Duty 4...  yeah, I miss my keyboard and mouse some, but the controller works, and I don't like lose my mind.  Most games limit you now in some way (2 guns, not 34895732045703298475...  single fire, not multiple types...  only one type of grenade at a time...  things like that) to handle controller capacity.  Would it be better on a keyboard and mouse?  Maybe, if they let you do more stuff, but they don't - you still only use WASD, your mouse to aim and fire, and a button to change weapons.  The ONLY thing the mouse gives you is more &quot;pinpoint&quot; aiming and most games nowaways that isn't a big deal, as they help you with that too.<br />
<br />
I love my PC, and it will always have games on it, of some kind.  But I also love my Xbox 360, and it will get it's share of time.  (My Dreamcast took time from my PC, so did my N64, so did my Gamecube, my PS2, my Xbox, etc - it's just gotten a larger share).  I also cannot pick up my PC, take it to a friend's house, and go &quot;hey, let's play this!&quot; or &quot;Hey, I got this, I think you'll like it.&quot;  It's why I'm still going to buy Prototype for my Xbox even though I bet it on PC...  I share with my friends, and they don't have gaming PCs, or even an xbox 360 (one of them has a wii, one has a ps2...  neither have gaming PCs, nor do they want one).</div>
		</td>
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/closeq.gif" width="30" height="30" align="right"></td>
  </tr>
</table>
</div><br />
So because you were running servers and couldn't easily download maps like the rest of the people, the rest of the people don't deserve to have it even though there is no hassle at all for them? Sure, if you want to experiment around the obscure  maps or just check them out on your own, you have to look for them, but if you are just connecting to a server for a quick game, the map(s) it is playing will be downloaded and there's no trouble to be had 99% of the time. <br />
<br />
What Halo 3 32 man games? There's no such thing, Halo 3, like a shitload of other games that offer MP on the consoles, caps out at 16 people and there are no dedicated servers for it. Afaik, most console games don't have dedicated servers, particularly on the XBox, and after looking the only two notable ones I can find on either console that do use them are Warhawk and Killzone 2 (both of which support 32 players because of this). Why do you think people are causing such a shitstorm about this? They know damn good and well that playing stuff on a non dedicated server sucks balls.<br />
<br />
As for the mods and stuff, I don't really see what your age has to do with anything. It seems to me that you just don't want to **** around with stuff out of laziness or something. I would hardly think that most modders or the people that use their mods are just a bunch of teenagers, especially the more skilled ones that do major things for games (EG: The stuff that makes up FCOM for Oblivion).<br />
<br />
Huge wall of text I saw posted somewhere else: <br />
