<a href="showpost.php?p=489408&amp;postcount=28" target="new" rel="nofollow" id="postcount489408" name="28" class="pcount"><strong>#28</strong></a>

			
		</td>
      </tr>
    </table>
    <div align="left">
	<hr align="left" width="100%" />

    <!-- message -->
    <div align="left" id="post_message_489408"><div align="center" style="margin:5px; margin-top:5px; ">
<table width="85%" border="0" align="center" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0" bgcolor="#333333" class="bbcodeQUOTE">
  
  <tr>
    <td colspan="3" align="center" valign="middle">
	
	<div align="left"><b><div align="left" style="font-size: 12px; color: #999999; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;"><strong>Nenjin said:</strong></div></b></div></td>
 
	</tr>
  <tr>   
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/openq.gif" width="30" height="30" ></td>
    <td>
		<div align="left" style="font-size: 12px; color: #999999; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;">Where gamers don't own the servers, they don't own the content (maps, skins, mods, what have you) and in some cases, where they don't even own physical copies of the games anymore.</div>
		</td>
    <td width="30" align="center" valign="middle"><img src="/forums/images/closeq.gif" width="30" height="30" align="right"></td>
  </tr>
</table>
</div>I dunno - sounds like EQ or WoW or any other mmorpg to me.  They (software companies) can do this and still have sufficient content to keep users interested enough for 15 bucks a month or whatever, but only through massive continuous investment in new content.<br />
<br />
As long as there is interesting new content coming, most folks don't care if it comes from users or devs.<br />
<br />
I assume x-mas crash, for instance, came from a user, but I don't care if it did or not, if you see what I mean.  New content means I'll play longer, and free new content that I enjoy means I'm more lilkely to give it the benefit of the doubt in making that decision - but I don't care where the content comes from.<br />
<br />
My point is that its not a new world (imo), its just the free market driving an equilibrium point;  what can you charge for vs what must you offer for free to keep folks paying SOMETHING to you.  Allowing users to provide free content to one another is one knob in that equation.  I don't see it as a foregone conclusion that knob is going to be turned to zero.</div>
    <!-- / message -->
    
    
