    <div align="left">
	<hr align="left" width="100%" />

    <!-- message -->
    <div align="left" id="post_message_489409">Yeah, the MMO model is something we readily accepted. But they're working with a different set of expectations than FPS or any other games. Your dependence on them to provide the network is explicit, so the game can live up the the MM part. The agreement that you're simply using a client to access the game is put right out front too. <br />
<br />
The shift to that kind of mentality by other games is happening more subtly elsewhere, through gaming networks. Like MMOs, they're making players dependent on them to fulfill the MP part, both to drive and protect profit. Other MP games want the same fidelity of sales that MMOs enjoy. <br />
<br />
I agree it's the market equalizing, but it will come with a reduction in user control and participation. You can see the market edging that way with things like OnLive, now that the tech has made it possible to keep gamers at arms length from the actual code. Lots of gamers are tinkerers or better and they've come to enjoy being included in the process of a game and its growth.</div>
    <!-- / message -->
    
    
    <br>
