    <!-- message -->
    <div align="left" id="post_message_489429">That is true - if I buy a game that is not an mmorpg, I expect it runs on my PC and I expect its much (extremely so) more likely that there will be user generated hacks or mods for the game - both the pve version and any pvp versions that might be part of the game.<br />
<br />
I see what you mean now by new world.<br />
<br />
It will take some time to find the balance, but I think the benefit of free content towards the goal of profit generation will keep companies enabling user generated content.<br />
<br />
Even WoW does it - I don't have data, but I'd be surprised if, to a good approximation, not all WoW players install interface add-ons.  Blizzard doesn't pay anyone to develop any of those, and some of them end up becoming very central to people's enjoyment of the game.  If Auctioneer breaks, for instance, people anecdotally start talking about all the folks they know who cancelled their accounts because they no longer enjoy the game and etc.<br />
<br />
Blizzard gets more revenue than they would if they didn't enable users to write interfaces for each other, and it doesn't cost them a penny in development costs.<br />
<br />
I think it would be the rare game where the most revenue would be generated only by preventing any free user content from being available.  Probably it will be common for user content to require some game company infrastructure that is charged for.  You can create all the maps you want, upload them to our server.  We then charge other users to access the server, or something like that.</div>
    <!-- / message -->
    
    
