</div>It's probably worth noting that each patch (especially major ones, but also occasionally minor ones) include updates, changes, and reductions to the API code that WoW addons utilize. It is costing Blizzard man hours to make those changes, to analyze the results of those changes, and to be aware of how the community is using the API. It's those man hours that have stopped things like waypoint mods, decursive, auto-rogue, and so forth.<br />
<br />
But your point does still stand: If the cost of producing and maintaining the API code is less than the revenue that the extra subscriptions they generate then all the better.</div>
