    <div align="left">
	<hr align="left" width="100%" />

    <!-- message -->
    <div align="left" id="post_message_490331">Price cuts won't ever happen, don't be silly.<br />
<br />
And, let's use Borderlands as an example here.  The PC game is a port from the consoles (unlike the past, where the console is a port of the PC version).  They release the PC game later than the console for &quot;extra QA testing,&quot;, and as we play the game we realize there's nothing different.  It's a console HUD/UI, the menus are HORRID to use with a keyboard/mouse (I try to hide my mouse when I do menus so I can just use the keyboard), and there's a lot of things that make no sense, until you go &quot;oh, right, console port.&quot;  Some of those things are silly, like...  tapping E picks things up, holding E &quot;swaps&quot; things, and double tapping E reloads, when the R button is right next to it.  That's a complete console carryover (where they don't have a dedicated reload button).  Also, you can't remap your keys in game, or adjust graphics settings.  They exist in the ini files, and folks who are playing it on the PC likely have the ability to go adjust them, but most folks won't make the effort.  Oh, those same ini files make for absurd things (aka, you can change the ini file to give yourself backpack slots, etc).  These same ini tweaks can break other people's save files, by the way - so be careful if you try to play a public game.  There's a save game editor that let's you change EVERYTHING about your character (including making guns from the existing parts, nothing &quot;new&quot; but you can cheat like hell).<br />
<br />
Also, using Borderlands as a test for no dedicated servers is stupid, Toprem.  They used GAMESPY as their way of doing online play - even for people who bought it through steam, which has a matchmaking service built in.  Gamespy sets the ports, not the Borderlands game, and yes, having to go through a router is terrible, if you don't know how to forward ports.  The consoles never have this issue (using XBL or PSN it just &quot;works&quot; since even without a dedicated server you connect to the XBL server to let everyone connect, basically).  However, as a PC gamer, you SHOULD have the ability to set yourself up - should you HAVE to?  No, but you should be able to.<br />
<br />
I really really doubt that Infinity Ward will end up using something you have to forward ports for.  I don't particularly care, myself - I've got my copy coming for my Xbox, and a new Xbox to match.  I've got Borderlands on both PC and Xbox - PC for online play, Xbox for local splitscreen (and the UI kinda sucks, even moreso splitscreen, but still fun as hell).  The ONLY thing I dislike about Borderlands (and this is on console OR PC) - if the host drops, you don't save.  Everyone has to log out first, THEN the host can quit.  That's horrible.  They need to patch that, for everything.  I also hate that the consoles got a patch to fix some of the major broken things...  and the PC has no patch (Phase Strike on the PC being just one example - still broken as hell).<br />
<br />
I think you're overreacting to the server thing - will it suck?  Probably not.  Is it a change?  Yes.  And 16v16 vs 9v9... if the maps are made for 9v9 and not 16v16, they'll be fine.  Was the decision made to do 9v9 for consoles, and PCs get the shaft?  Probably.  Does it mean it will be horrible?  Probably not.<br />
<br />
The times, they are a changin'</div>
